Car Plate Character Segmenttion¶

Reference："Detecting the Car Number Plate Using Segmentation" V. Lakshmi Priya 1, K. Perumal2¶

You'd better read this paper to get a feeling on how to detect the car plate numbers. You can find this paper in the project papers subfolder. We also provide a few related papers for your reference.

4. Label and Region Proposal¶

In [520]:
label_img = measure.label(img4)
regions = measure.regionprops(label_img)
In [559]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.imshow(img, cmap=plt.cm.gray)

def in_bboxes(bbox, bboxes):
    for bb in bboxes:
        minr0, minc0, maxr0, maxc0 = bb
        minr1, minc1, maxr1, maxc1 = bbox
        if minr1 >= minr0 and maxr1 <= maxr0 and minc1 >= minc0 and maxc1 <= maxc0:
            return True
    return False

bboxes = []
for props in regions:
    y0, x0 = props.centroid
    minr, minc, maxr, maxc = props.bbox
    
    if maxc - minc > img4.shape[1] / 7 or maxr - minr < img4.shape[0] / 3:
        continue
        
    bbox = [minr, minc, maxr, maxc]
    if in_bboxes(bbox, bboxes):
        continue
        
    if abs(y0 - img4.shape[0] / 2) > img4.shape[0] / 4:
        continue
    
    # delete the things which is not wide enough
    if (maxr-minr)/(maxc-minc)>5:
        continue
       
    if(minr > 100):
        minr = 50
        bbox = [minr, minc-2, maxr, maxc+2]
    if minr <10:
        minr = 20
        bbox = [minr, minc, maxr, maxc]   
    
    bboxes.append(bbox)
    
    bx = (minc, maxc, maxc, minc, minc)
    by = (minr, minr, maxr, maxr, minr)
    ax.plot(bx, by, '-r', linewidth=2)

6. Image Enhancement¶

In order to improve the recognition rate, it may need to do image enhancement before character recognition.

In this part, i use median filter in order to make the image enhancement

In [557]:
# as for the first image, we can have four ways to use it, thus we shown
import numpy as np
from scipy import ndimage as ndi
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.cm as cm

from skimage import transform
from skimage import data
from skimage import color
from skimage.util import view_as_blocks
from skimage import data, exposure

# input the image
l = transform.resize(ch, (80,44))

# define the shape of sample block
block_shape = (2,2)

# transfer the image into the matrix block
view = view_as_blocks(l, block_shape)
# print(l.shape)  # output(80, 44)
# print(view.shape) # output(20, 11, 4, 4)

# let the last two dimension of view into one dimension
flatten_view = view.reshape(view.shape[0], view.shape[1], -1)
# print(flatten_view.shape) # output(20, 11,16)

# generate the picture by average value, max value and median value
mean_view = np.mean(flatten_view, axis=2)
# print(mean_view.shape) # output(20, 11)
max_view = np.max(flatten_view, axis=2)
median_view = np.median(flatten_view, axis=2)

# display the image after sampling
fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(8, 8), sharex=True, sharey=True)
# print(axes.shape) # output(2,2)

# make the ax into one dimention
ax = axes.ravel()
# print(ax.shape) # output(4,)

# Original rescaled with spline interpolation (order=3
l_resized = ndi.zoom(l, 2, order=3)
# print(l_resized.shape) # output(160, 88)

ax[0].set_title("Original rescaled with\n spline interpolation (order=3)")
ax[0].imshow(l_resized, extent=(0, 22, 40, 0),cmap=cm.Greys_r)

ax[1].set_title("Block view with\n local mean pooling")
ax[1].imshow(mean_view, cmap=cm.Greys_r)

ax[2].set_title("Block view with\n local max pooling")
ax[2].imshow(max_view, cmap=cm.Greys_r)

ax[3].set_title("Block view with\n local median pooling")
ax[3].imshow(median_view, cmap=cm.Greys_r)

for a in ax:
    a.set_axis_off()

fig.tight_layout()
plt.show()
In [555]:
chars = []
for bbox in bboxes:
    minr, minc, maxr, maxc = bbox
    ch = img2[minr:maxr, minc:maxc]
    
    # resize the image
    l = transform.resize(ch, (80,44))
    
    # define the shape of sample block
    block_shape = (2,2)
    
    # transfer the image into the matrix block
    view = view_as_blocks(l, block_shape)
    
    # let the last two dimension of view into one dimension
    flatten_view = view.reshape(view.shape[0], view.shape[1], -1)
    
    # get the median view of the picture
    median_view = np.max(flatten_view, axis=2)
    
    # become darker to delete the noise
    dark_view = exposure.adjust_gamma(median_view, 1.5)
    
    # write into the chars list
    chars.append(dark_view)
    
    io.imshow(dark_view, cmap=cm.Greys_r)
    
    plt.show()

7. Character Recognition¶

In [546]:
import tensorflow.compat.v1 as tf
tf.disable_v2_behavior()

import keras
from keras.datasets import mnist
from keras.models import Sequential
from keras.layers import Dense, Dropout, Flatten
from keras.layers import Conv2D, MaxPooling2D
from keras import backend as K

DATASET_DIR = './dataset'
classes = os.listdir(DATASET_DIR )

num_classes = len(classes)
img_rows, img_cols = 20, 20

if K.image_data_format() == 'channels_first':
    input_shape = [1, img_rows, img_cols]
else:
    input_shape = [img_rows, img_cols, 1]

7.1 Create a cnn model for character recognition¶

Here is a sample model. You can fine tune this model or build a different model to order to improve the accuracy.

In [547]:
# we provide a sample model here, 
# you can use other model as you like
model_char = Sequential()
model_char.add(Conv2D(32, kernel_size=(3, 3),
                 activation='relu',
                 input_shape=input_shape))
model_char.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
model_char.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
model_char.add(Dropout(0.25))
model_char.add(Flatten())
model_char.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
model_char.add(Dropout(0.5))
model_char.add(Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax'))

model_char.compile(loss=keras.losses.categorical_crossentropy,
              optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adadelta(),
              metrics=['accuracy'])

We use pretrained character recognition model to recognize car plate characters.

def extend_channel(data):
    if K.image_data_format() == 'channels_first':
        data = data.reshape(data.shape[0], 1, img_rows, img_cols)
    else:
        data = data.reshape(data.shape[0], img_rows, img_cols, 1)
        
    return data
